and get on with the show.

09:58.498 --> 10:00.668
Shall we get on
with the show?

10:00.668 --> 10:02.335
Let's do it.

10:23.256 --> 10:24.958
Thank you, everybody!

10:24.958 --> 10:26.894
Thank you so much.

10:26.894 --> 10:31.364
And welcome
to the first ever Grand Tour.

10:35.602 --> 10:40.573
Thank you. Now, we hope
you like our tent.

10:40.573 --> 10:44.377
We think the great thing
is that because it roams
around the world,

10:44.377 --> 10:47.715
we get a different view
out of the big picture
windows every week.

10:47.715 --> 10:49.750
So this week,
obviously we've got

10:49.750 --> 10:51.118
the high desert
of California.

10:51.118 --> 10:54.254
- Next week, who knows?
- I do.

10:54.254 --> 10:58.325
Well, yes, James, we know.
It's Johannesburg.

10:58.325 --> 11:01.729
- Now they know.
- I know they know!
It doesn't matter!

11:01.729 --> 11:04.765
The point is the view changes
and so does the audience, okay?

11:04.765 --> 11:07.267
This week
you're all Americans.

11:07.267 --> 11:09.202
[CHEERING]

11:14.742 --> 11:17.077
Now, this is a bit
of a problem

11:17.077 --> 11:20.113
for people like us
who speak English.

11:20.113 --> 11:24.351
We can converse perfectly well
in a shop or a restaurant,

11:24.351 --> 11:27.054
but when it comes
to cars and motoring,

11:27.054 --> 11:29.857
every single word you use
is different.

11:29.857 --> 11:33.160
When I say "different,"
I mean "wrong."

11:33.160 --> 11:35.562
When you change gear
with a lever,
what do you call that?

11:35.562 --> 11:38.131
- Stick.
- Stick.

11:38.131 --> 11:40.133
Now, you see,
this is a stick.

11:40.133 --> 11:42.402
Couldn't change gear
with this.

11:42.402 --> 11:45.105
Wouldn't work.
What you can do with this
is point at things.

11:45.105 --> 11:47.140
Let's see
if we can get you educated.

11:47.140 --> 11:49.109
What do you call
this bit of a car?

11:49.109 --> 11:52.145
- ALL: The hood!
- MAN: Bonnet.

11:52.145 --> 11:54.681
- Bonnet.
- They're learning.

11:54.681 --> 11:57.785
What do you mean?
I know you can wear
a bonnet on your head.

11:57.785 --> 12:02.455
It's two things.
We're capable of having
those different thoughts.

12:02.455 --> 12:04.892
- What type
of vehicle is this?
- ALL: Pick-up.

12:04.892 --> 12:06.493
No, it's stupid.

12:06.493 --> 12:09.797
- Oh, now, hang on.
- It is stupid.

12:09.797 --> 12:12.132
Let's do another one of these.

12:12.132 --> 12:16.036
- What type
of vehicle is this?
- ALL: Coupe.

12:16.036 --> 12:20.073
Coupe? Coop is where
you keep your chickens.

12:20.073 --> 12:22.342
That's a coupé.
That's a French word, I admit.

12:22.342 --> 12:24.511
- Yeah, a bit.
- They're muddled with that.

12:24.511 --> 12:27.280
George Bush, have you heard what
he once said about the French?

12:27.280 --> 12:29.082
"The trouble with the French is
they have no word

12:29.082 --> 12:30.851
for entrepreneur."

12:32.252 --> 12:34.421
It is difficult. I think
the only thing we agree on

12:34.421 --> 12:36.656
- is "steering wheel."
- Yeah.

12:36.656 --> 12:40.861
But then they go and put it
on the wrong side of the car.

12:40.861 --> 12:45.298
It must be really annoying
having to drive along
like that all the time.

12:45.298 --> 12:49.002
Why don't you just put it
in front of the driver
like we do?

12:49.002 --> 12:51.438
It's probably a good idea
if we get on with
the actual show.

12:51.438 --> 12:53.841
Yes, it is. But we had
to clear all that up,

12:53.841 --> 12:56.176
because contrary to what
some people have been saying,

12:56.176 --> 12:58.578
this actually is a car show.

12:58.578 --> 13:01.314
- Well, not next week it isn't.
- Next week is an exception.

13:01.314 --> 13:03.116
- Yeah.
- But not when we go
to Barbados either.

13:03.116 --> 13:05.152
No, Barbados is definitely
another exception.

13:05.152 --> 13:08.989
But tonight couldn't be
more "car-y" if it tried.

13:08.989 --> 13:12.159
I'm gonna prove that point
because we're kicking off
with this.

13:13.861 --> 13:16.196
[LAUGHTER AND JEERING]

13:16.196 --> 13:19.132
Bear with me, bear with me--

13:19.132 --> 13:21.935
- I agree!
- [LAUGHTER]

13:21.935 --> 13:23.103
The thing is, though,

13:23.103 --> 13:25.505
various supercar makers
have now taken

13:25.505 --> 13:29.342
the polar-bear-friendly
technology from a Prius,

13:29.342 --> 13:33.146
and they are now using it
to create raw, naked speed.

13:33.146 --> 13:36.416
Now, I say the best
of these hybrid hypercars

13:36.416 --> 13:40.787
is the mad,
swivel-eyed McLaren P1.

13:40.787 --> 13:42.890
Whereas Richard Hammond,
who's wrong--

13:42.890 --> 13:43.991
I'm not wrong.

13:43.991 --> 13:46.259
He is, because he says
the best

13:46.259 --> 13:49.462
is actually the rather
boring Porsche 918.

13:49.462 --> 13:51.999
- It's not boring!
- Yes, it is.

13:51.999 --> 13:54.001
- It isn't.
- Mm-hmm.

13:54.001 --> 13:55.535
It isn't.
Well, whatever.

13:55.535 --> 13:59.106
We decided to meet up
with the cars

13:59.106 --> 14:01.574
and settle this
once and for all.

14:59.332 --> 15:04.237
The location we chose
for this titanic duel
was Portugal...

15:04.237 --> 15:09.176
