19:25.965 --> 19:30.002
Absolutely brilliant.

19:30.002 --> 19:32.038
Oh.

19:32.038 --> 19:34.073
What a car.

19:34.073 --> 19:35.575
I love it.

19:38.245 --> 19:41.080
- Well?
- This is rubbish!

19:41.080 --> 19:43.450
I was just thinking exactly
the same about this.

19:43.450 --> 19:45.151
- Were you?
- This was boring me to death.

19:45.151 --> 19:49.656
It was like being stuck
in a Victorian woman's novel.

19:49.656 --> 19:53.526
I'd rather that than being
stuck in a telephone box
with a panicking gorilla.

19:53.526 --> 19:55.562
- Rubbish.
- It was trying to kill me.

19:55.562 --> 19:57.597
- It wants to hurt me.
- That's why I like it.

19:57.597 --> 19:59.899
This is
a missionary-position car.

19:59.899 --> 20:01.968
Razor blade
in the hands of a surgeon.

20:01.968 --> 20:05.238
Sickle in the hands
of a drunk peasant.

20:05.238 --> 20:08.908
Downton Abbey. Breaking Bad.
That's crystal meth.

20:08.908 --> 20:10.577
That's some iffy weed.

20:10.577 --> 20:14.213
Fine wine.
Crate of Newcy Brown.

20:15.282 --> 20:18.318
Schooner of sherry.
Absinthe.

20:18.318 --> 20:20.086
James Bond specifying

20:20.086 --> 20:22.121
his martini to be shaken
not stirred.

20:22.121 --> 20:23.656
Begbie in Trainspotting

20:23.656 --> 20:25.458
lobbing a pint pot over
his shoulder in a night club

20:25.458 --> 20:28.261
and starting a bar fight.
What?

20:33.165 --> 20:34.834
Hi.

20:34.834 --> 20:36.669
What are you doing here?

20:36.669 --> 20:38.705
I'm here because, gentlemen,

20:38.705 --> 20:40.740
I have in the back
of that lorry

20:40.740 --> 20:43.576
something that will make
your McLaren and your Porsche

20:43.576 --> 20:45.978
look like lumps of yesteryear.

20:52.084 --> 20:54.020
[REVVING]

21:13.973 --> 21:15.875
I cannot remember
the last time a car,

21:15.875 --> 21:17.777
or, indeed,
any sort of thing,

21:17.777 --> 21:20.580
gave me a fizz like
the Ferrari LaFerrari.

21:22.349 --> 21:25.385
This has 950 horsepower.

21:25.385 --> 21:26.886
950.

21:28.355 --> 21:30.189
More than either
of the other two.

21:30.189 --> 21:32.992
And it's lighter.
It weighs 1,250 kilograms.

21:35.928 --> 21:38.898
Which is less
than most hatchbacks.

21:41.601 --> 21:43.870
Actually there is a bit more
to the Ferrari LaFerrari,

21:43.870 --> 21:48.675
because what it has is,
in effect, a formula one
KERS system.

21:48.675 --> 21:53.546
It constantly recovers energy
that would otherwise be lost

21:53.546 --> 21:55.948
using its electric motor
and its battery.

21:55.948 --> 21:58.751
So as I brake there,

21:58.751 --> 22:02.622
the car is actually saying,
"That energy, I'll have that."

22:03.890 --> 22:05.825
Straight!

22:07.026 --> 22:10.630
This is what 950 horsepower
feels like!

22:15.301 --> 22:17.437
Jesus!

22:21.273 --> 22:25.678
This I believe will absolutely
mince the other two.

22:25.678 --> 22:27.580
Oh, man!

22:29.315 --> 22:32.485
JEREMY: James was obviously
talking nonsense.

22:32.485 --> 22:34.787
But there's no getting
around the fact

22:34.787 --> 22:37.023
that these three cars
take automotive science

22:37.023 --> 22:38.958
to a new level.

22:41.260 --> 22:43.963
They use
the latest green technology

22:43.963 --> 22:46.733
to squeeze
as much speed as possible

22:46.733 --> 22:49.536
from every molecule of fuel.

22:51.070 --> 22:54.240
As a result, they're
all capable of blasting

22:54.240 --> 22:56.676
way past 200 miles an hour

22:56.676 --> 23:00.947
whilst producing fewer
harmful emissions
than a family saloon.

23:06.352 --> 23:11.057
What we have here, then,
are three incredible machines

23:11.057 --> 23:12.892
which, at a stroke,

23:12.892 --> 23:16.128
have made the traditional
supercar look wooden...

23:16.128 --> 23:18.064
and old-fashioned.

23:20.867 --> 23:24.637
Welcome, everyone,
to the hypercar holy trinity.

23:28.040 --> 23:32.745
In that door mirror
I have a £1 million Porsche.

23:32.745 --> 23:36.883
In that door mirror
I have a £1 million Ferrari.

23:39.218 --> 23:40.820
What a toy box today.

23:47.660 --> 23:49.796
Sparks from Jezzer.

23:56.268 --> 23:58.204
I don't think so, Hammond.

23:58.204 --> 24:00.139
[TIRES SQUEALING]

24:05.745 --> 24:07.880
This could be so expensive.

24:17.724 --> 24:19.759
It's going to boost.

24:19.759 --> 24:22.128
Pushing the IPAS button!

24:22.128 --> 24:26.132
And that gives me
another 170 horsepower.

24:26.132 --> 24:27.800
[LAUGHING]

24:28.935 --> 24:30.737
Opening DRS!

24:32.539 --> 24:34.541
Oh, my Christ!

24:34.541 --> 24:36.909
Bloody...

24:36.909 --> 24:39.746
And here comes May
in the Ferrari LaFerrari.

24:44.984 --> 24:47.954
Concentrating.
Concentrating.

24:59.832 --> 25:02.234
Oh-oh! That bloody car

25:02.234 --> 25:04.236
is trying to kill me,
and I'm not even in it.

25:07.139 --> 25:08.908
Ha-ha!

25:19.586 --> 25:22.454
JEREMY: We could have played
out there all day,

25:22.454 --> 25:26.092
but before we ended up
in a £3 million crash,

25:26.092 --> 25:28.127
we decided to start
the tests

25:28.127 --> 25:30.963
to see which
of the cars was best.

25:30.963 --> 25:32.632
I came up with the first one,

25:32.632 --> 25:36.102
mainly to annoy
gate-crasher May.

25:36.102 --> 25:39.105
Let's make the first test
a drag race

25:39.105 --> 25:43.042
- using electrical power only.
- Good idea.

25:43.042 --> 25:45.778
- It isn't a good idea.
- Why not?

25:45.778 --> 25:48.615
Because you can't drive
the Ferrari on electrical
power only.

25:48.615 --> 25:51.618
- No!
- Of course you can't,

25:51.618 --> 25:53.686
because it's a KERS system
like a Formula One car.

25:53.686 --> 25:56.623
It's got a V12 engine
and an electric motor,

25:56.623 --> 25:59.391
but they are integrated,
they work together,
you can't separate them.

25:59.391 --> 26:03.129
- You should have thought
about that, shouldn't you?
- Bad planning.

26:04.831 --> 26:07.634
With James reduced
to the role of onlooker,

26:07.634 --> 26:11.170
we lined up the P1 and
the 918 on the start line,

26:11.170 --> 26:15.274
but then, instead of
revving the petrol engines,

26:15.274 --> 26:17.644
we shut them down.

26:21.848 --> 26:23.883
That is weird.

26:23.883 --> 26:27.186
Preparing to start a drag race

26:27.186 --> 26:29.555
in complete silence.

26:29.555 --> 26:32.191
I still have
two electric motors

26:32.191 --> 26:35.527
that together produce
285 brake horsepower

26:35.527 --> 26:37.163
which is 109 more

26:37.163 --> 26:42.301
than the one electric motor
in his McLaren. Oh, yeah.

26:43.535 --> 26:46.172
[BEEPING]

26:47.273 --> 26:49.175
[BEEP AND KLAXON]

26:52.679 --> 26:54.847
I'm outta here!

26:54.847 --> 26:57.483
You've got to love that,
the immediate power

26:57.483 --> 26:59.919
from an electrical engine.

26:59.919 --> 27:03.956
That is 70 miles an hour
already and it isn't enough.

27:03.956 --> 27:05.858
[RICHARD LAUGHING]

27:08.327 --> 27:10.697
[LAUGHING]

27:16.703 --> 27:19.772
Who won that?
It was me, wasn't it?

27:19.772 --> 27:21.808
Yeah, but it's not
important though, is it?

27:21.808 --> 27:23.575
- Is it not?
- It's just not relevant.

27:23.575 --> 27:25.177
Right, right.

27:25.177 --> 27:27.880
In a drag race, it's irrelevant
which car gets there first?

27:27.880 --> 27:31.117
Yeah, yours is
the better milk float.

27:31.117 --> 27:33.585
[LAUGHS]

27:33.585 --> 27:38.024
Back in the pits, Hammond had
an idea for the next test.

27:38.024 --> 27:41.227
We've got to drive
to the hotel yet.
It's about an hour away.

27:41.227 --> 27:43.730
It gives us a chance to see
what they're like on the road.

27:43.730 --> 27:46.165
- That's a good point.
- Real world.

27:46.165 --> 27:49.235
- That is a good point.
- I can't do that.

27:49.235 --> 27:51.270
I can't drive the Ferrari
on the road.

27:51.270 --> 27:53.605
- Why?
- It's not registered.

27:53.605 --> 27:55.341
It is,
it's got number plates.

27:55.341 --> 27:57.209
No, that's just pretend
number plates.

27:57.209 --> 27:59.145
If they register it,
it becomes second-hand

27:59.145 --> 28:00.947
and they pay tax. That's
why it came in the lorry.

28:00.947 --> 28:02.982
So you can't drive it
on the road either?

28:02.982 --> 28:05.017
Nobody can drive it.
It's not road legal.

28:05.017 --> 28:07.754
- Oh, no.
- Mate, that's...

28:07.754 --> 28:10.356
- That is such a shame.
- It's an hour of--

28:10.356 --> 28:12.491
That's really a rotten bit
of luck.

28:12.491 --> 28:14.626
'Cause you've come a long way
from Italy.

28:14.626 --> 28:16.495
I can't give you a lift

28:16.495 --> 28:19.365
'cause the soundman's headphones
are on the seat and the mixer.

28:19.365 --> 28:21.167
JAMES: Oh, no.

28:21.167 --> 28:23.069
There's literally
nothing I can do.

28:26.338 --> 28:28.307
Soon Richard
and I were enjoying

28:28.307 --> 28:31.778
the world's
best-ever commute.

28:39.218 --> 28:41.253
It may be a bit Spartan
in here,

28:41.253 --> 28:43.790
but it's unbelievably
comfortable.

28:44.690 --> 28:47.960
Because it uses electronics

28:47.960 --> 28:50.229
rather than traditional
anti-roll bars.

28:50.229 --> 28:52.464
That means there's
no physical connection

28:52.464 --> 28:54.300
between the wheels.

28:54.300 --> 28:58.437
So if one goes over a bump
the others aren't affected.

28:58.437 --> 29:01.473
It's uncanny. It's like being
in a Rolls-Royce Phantom.

29:04.977 --> 29:08.714
It's a lovely evening.
Taken the roof panels out.

29:08.714 --> 29:10.817
Set the air-con just so.

29:10.817 --> 29:12.919
And I'm enjoying
a drive in the country.

29:21.393 --> 29:22.962
[CHUCKLES]

29:26.532 --> 29:28.467
JEREMY: Meanwhile...

29:57.997 --> 29:59.165
[CHUCKLES]

30:03.069 --> 30:06.272
JAMES: Oh, bloody hell.

30:06.272 --> 30:08.207
[BEEPING]

30:09.375 --> 30:11.210
You're all right.

30:11.210 --> 30:13.679
You're all right,
in Italian.

30:13.679 --> 30:15.814
[CAR HORN]

30:18.750 --> 30:20.887
[CAR HORNS]

30:22.354 --> 30:24.390
Oh, God.

30:24.390 --> 30:26.325
[CHEERING]

30:30.362 --> 30:32.331
- James.
- What?

30:32.331 --> 30:35.902
I'm sorry to have to say this,
but that Ferrari is useless.

30:35.902 --> 30:38.637
Yes, yes, yes.
Later on in part two,

30:38.637 --> 30:40.940
when these two have stopped
dreaming up

30:40.940 --> 30:42.641
idiotic and irrelevant tests

30:42.641 --> 30:46.478
that it can't take part in,
we shall see.

30:46.478 --> 30:48.314
Fair enough. Now,

30:48.314 --> 30:50.816
at this point in the show
we like to sit down

30:50.816 --> 30:54.286
and chew the fat about new
cars and motoring issues.

30:54.286 --> 30:57.990
Like, for example,
why in Britain we have
to drive at 50 miles an hour

30:57.990 --> 31:01.627
when they're doing roadworks
to protect the workforce
which is never there.

31:01.627 --> 31:03.329
Yes, okay...

31:03.329 --> 31:05.331
And why fully-grown adults

31:05.331 --> 31:08.767
have taken to riding around
the city on children's toys?

31:08.767 --> 31:11.270
- Yes, okay.
- I think they're
called bicycles.

31:11.270 --> 31:13.839
- Is that the right word?
- It's issues like that.

31:13.839 --> 31:17.209
It's a segment we are calling
Conversation Street.

31:17.209 --> 31:19.345
♫♫ [JAZZY TUNE]

31:22.848 --> 31:24.616
[LAUGHTER]

31:24.616 --> 31:27.653
- Well...
- What?

31:27.653 --> 31:29.688
[CHEERING]

31:29.688 --> 31:32.024
We put a lot of work into that!

31:32.024 --> 31:35.962
It was really,
really hard doing that.

31:35.962 --> 31:39.365
Better than that, rather
brilliantly, we have made

31:39.365 --> 31:41.733
a bespoke version
of that sting

31:41.733 --> 31:43.269
for every single episode

31:43.269 --> 31:45.504
we're gonna make
for the next three years.

31:45.504 --> 31:47.539
How about that?

31:47.539 --> 31:49.641
[CHEERING]

31:49.641 --> 31:51.877
But hold on.
The slight problem with that

31:51.877 --> 31:53.712
is that we were
so busy doing that

31:53.712 --> 31:56.682
we didn't think actually
of anything to talk about.

31:56.682 --> 31:58.517
- We did.
- Yeah.

31:58.517 --> 32:00.752
- What?
- You'll love this.

32:00.752 --> 32:06.658
James May, the world's
slowest moving human being,

32:06.658 --> 32:10.029
has been caught speeding.

32:10.029 --> 32:12.698
[GASPS OF SURPRISE]

32:12.698 --> 32:14.500
Actually charged
by the police.

32:14.500 --> 32:17.169
Criminal.

32:17.169 --> 32:18.704
He's actually quite proud of it.

32:18.704 --> 32:22.208
He did it on a Honda
CBR 600RR sports bike.

32:23.909 --> 32:25.177
The thing was...

32:25.177 --> 32:27.613
[OVERLAPPING CHATTER]

32:27.613 --> 32:30.316
Richard and I were
genuinely astonished.

32:30.316 --> 32:31.750
He came into the office
and said,

32:31.750 --> 32:34.153
"I've been done
for speeding."

32:34.153 --> 32:37.123
Until we found out
how fast he was going.

32:37.123 --> 32:39.558
James, how fast was it again?

32:39.558 --> 32:42.161
37 miles an hour.

32:42.161 --> 32:45.397
Crazy! Mad man!

32:45.397 --> 32:48.467
How did you even breathe
at that kind of speed?

32:48.467 --> 32:51.503
How did the police catch you?
Were they running?

32:52.938 --> 32:55.374
Gentle jog for sure.

32:55.374 --> 32:57.409
The thing is,
if you've been caught,

32:57.409 --> 32:59.778
'cause we genuinely don't
believe anyone in the world has,

32:59.778 --> 33:04.583
but if you've been caught
speeding at a speed less
than 37,

33:04.583 --> 33:07.653
do honestly please write
to us and let us know.

33:07.653 --> 33:09.688
'Cause we don't think
it's possible.

33:09.688 --> 33:12.458
And mark your envelope,
"I'm a tortoise."

33:12.458 --> 33:14.660
And that is all
we have time for this week

33:14.660 --> 33:16.095
on Conversation Street.

33:16.095 --> 33:17.463
- Whoa! Hang on a minute.
- What?

33:17.463 --> 33:18.830
The first-ever show,
and you just mock me

33:18.830 --> 33:21.300
for my speeding ticket
and then we move on?

33:21.300 --> 33:23.302
It's a busy show.

33:23.302 --> 33:26.372
It is a busy show.
We've got to tell everyone
about our track.

33:26.372 --> 33:29.441
- Yes, we have one.
- [CHEERING]

33:29.441 --> 33:32.378
This is the sort of place
where you can drive cars

33:32.378 --> 33:34.346
at speeds that you can do
on the road

33:34.346 --> 33:36.948
but only if you want
to go to prison afterwards.

33:36.948 --> 33:38.750
What, like 38 miles an hour?

33:38.750 --> 33:42.454
39 maybe even,
40 from time to time.

33:42.454 --> 33:44.423
Now, we were hoping
that we could bring it

33:44.423 --> 33:46.425
round the world with us
like the tent.

33:46.425 --> 33:50.229
But unfortunately
it's too heavy,

33:50.229 --> 33:53.099
and, as you are about to see,
too bitey.

33:57.869 --> 33:59.905
This is it.

33:59.905 --> 34:01.740
It's not a race circuit.

34:01.740 --> 34:04.843
It's not an airfield.

34:04.843 --> 34:07.379
It's not a road.

34:07.379 --> 34:10.716
What it is
is brilliant and fast.

34:11.950 --> 34:14.120
And extremely dangerous.

34:15.554 --> 34:17.823
It even looks dangerous
on a map.

34:17.823 --> 34:21.160
Because as you can see,
it's the exact same shape

34:21.160 --> 34:23.295
as the Ebola virus.

34:25.564 --> 34:29.635
Right, time now to show you
what a lap looks like.

34:29.635 --> 34:33.139
To do that we've got a bit of
a performance benchmark.

34:33.139 --> 34:35.141
A Ferrari 488.

34:35.141 --> 34:37.143
Take it away.

34:37.143 --> 34:39.178
[REVVING]

34:39.178 --> 34:40.779
Take it away.

34:43.582 --> 34:45.951
First up,
it's the Isn't Straight,

34:45.951 --> 34:49.455
so called because
it isn't straight.

34:49.455 --> 34:53.959
There is a super-fast left
followed by a super-fast right.

34:53.959 --> 34:57.863
And if you make a mistake,
there's no run-off area
or Armco.

34:57.863 --> 35:01.167
It's just woods.

35:01.167 --> 35:03.169
Woods that are full of wildlife

35:03.169 --> 35:05.871
which likes to run out
in front of you.

35:08.240 --> 35:11.410
After the second right
on the Isn't Straight,

35:11.410 --> 35:14.180
we're into
Your Name Here Corner.

35:15.714 --> 35:18.450
Sponsorship opportunities
are available here.

35:18.450 --> 35:20.486
However, I should explain

35:20.486 --> 35:23.589
that it's possible nobody
will be looking at your banner

35:23.589 --> 35:25.957
because this is a corner
that was designed

35:25.957 --> 35:28.427
so a car can do this.

35:40.339 --> 35:41.840
[TIRES SCREECH]

35:41.840 --> 35:43.108
Ladies and gentlemen,

35:43.108 --> 35:46.245
James May...
isn't here today.

35:46.245 --> 35:47.679
That's just a friend
of mine

35:47.679 --> 35:51.850
on his way back up
the Isn't Straight...

35:51.850 --> 35:54.220
towards Old Lady's House.

35:55.787 --> 35:58.457
We've called this section
Old Lady's House,

35:58.457 --> 36:00.492
because it's right next
to a house

36:00.492 --> 36:04.129
where an old lady lives.

36:04.129 --> 36:06.998
She tells us she likes cars.

36:06.998 --> 36:09.835
Says she used to have one.

36:09.835 --> 36:12.771
Not sure she's going
to like them quite so much

36:12.771 --> 36:14.773
after we've been here
a few times.

36:14.773 --> 36:17.909
[TIRES SQUEALING]

36:17.909 --> 36:20.779
Next up, there's a narrow
and bumpy sprint

36:20.779 --> 36:23.515
to Sub Station.

36:23.515 --> 36:25.884
You need to get
this 90-left right,

36:25.884 --> 36:28.887
or you'll crash into
a cage full of electricity.

36:31.056 --> 36:34.360
And you'll need to get the
final 90-left right as well,

36:34.360 --> 36:36.928
or you'll run into
a field of sheep.

36:40.799 --> 36:43.001
So, trees, animals,

36:43.001 --> 36:44.936
a house, electricity,

36:44.936 --> 36:46.772
and because it's in England,

36:46.772 --> 36:48.940
usually quite a lot
of moisture in the air.

36:48.940 --> 36:53.345
It really is the most dangerous
track anywhere in the world.

36:53.345 --> 36:55.381
To post a fast time here,

36:55.381 --> 36:59.017
you do need...

36:59.017 --> 37:00.952
those.

37:06.758 --> 37:09.728
The car I've selected
for my first lap

37:09.728 --> 37:12.364
of the Eboladrome
is this.

37:15.967 --> 37:18.404
The BMW M2.

37:32.784 --> 37:35.987
Sadly, there isn't the time
in this, our first-ever show,

37:35.987 --> 37:39.558
to do a full road test
of this car,

37:39.558 --> 37:42.894
but there is time
to say that I think

37:42.894 --> 37:46.798
this is the best M car
BMW has ever made.

38:00.346 --> 38:02.381
In a lot of fast cars
these days,

38:02.381 --> 38:04.550
you get all sorts
of knobs and buttons

38:04.550 --> 38:07.353
which you can use
to change--

38:07.353 --> 38:08.654
I say change--
I mean ruin

38:08.654 --> 38:10.088
the characteristics
of the engine

38:10.088 --> 38:12.958
and the suspension
and the steering and so on.

38:12.958 --> 38:15.160
And I always think,
isn't that like a chef

38:15.160 --> 38:16.995
bringing a fish to your table

38:16.995 --> 38:19.598
and an oven and some butter
and a bit of parsley,

38:19.598 --> 38:21.600
and saying,
"Cook it yourself"? No.

38:21.600 --> 38:23.969
You cook it,
it's what I'm paying for.

38:25.371 --> 38:27.373
This car, happily,
has a more

38:27.373 --> 38:29.207
back-to-basics approach.

38:29.207 --> 38:32.043
In the M2, you get a little
rocker switch down here

38:32.043 --> 38:34.746
which does nothing at all

38:34.746 --> 38:37.849
as far as I can see,
and that's it.

38:37.849 --> 38:40.786
You're buying a car
which was set up at the factory

38:40.786 --> 38:44.490
by engineers who know
what they're doing.

38:44.490 --> 38:47.025
And all you have to do
is enjoy it.

38:49.227 --> 38:50.962
Which I am doing.

38:57.002 --> 38:58.670
Yes, look at this.

38:58.670 --> 39:00.906
Oh, yeah, loving that.

39:00.906 --> 39:02.741
[CHUCKLES]

39:02.741 --> 39:05.611
I'll do that again, actually,
and make sure--

39:05.611 --> 39:07.879
make sure I was correct.

39:15.421 --> 39:16.755
There's hardly
any understeer at all.

39:16.755 --> 39:20.158
Poke the back out
and hold it there.

39:20.158 --> 39:22.994
Yeah!
[LAUGHS]

39:22.994 --> 39:24.830
I'll do that again...

39:24.830 --> 39:26.632
only going the other way.

39:26.632 --> 39:28.767
Wrong way round
Your Name Here.

39:31.570 --> 39:36.174
Klaus and Fritz,
I am loving your work.

39:36.174 --> 39:39.945
Oh, I made a mess of that.
But I'll just do this,

39:39.945 --> 39:42.614
and it'll look like
I did it on purpose.

39:44.082 --> 39:46.518
With the tires begging
for mercy,

39:46.518 --> 39:48.219
I got back onto the Isn't

39:48.219 --> 39:52.090
and unleashed
365 rampaging horsepowers

39:52.090 --> 39:55.761
from the turbo-charged
three-liter straight six.

39:57.496 --> 40:00.466
This isn't as fast
in a straight line

40:00.466 --> 40:03.234
as an M3,
but everywhere else...

40:03.234 --> 40:05.070
it is better.

40:05.070 --> 40:08.540
It feels less heavy,
less cumbersome.

40:14.079 --> 40:17.616
And due to the unique
characteristics
of our straight,

40:17.616 --> 40:20.552
I can tell the steering
is less...

40:20.552 --> 40:22.921
It's less twitchy.

40:27.593 --> 40:31.296
This track was designed
to trip cars up.

40:31.296 --> 40:33.465
There are fast corners,

40:33.465 --> 40:35.333
slow corners,

40:35.333 --> 40:37.836
drifty corners, and bumps.

40:37.836 --> 40:40.171
It's hard on the tires.

40:40.171 --> 40:43.775
It's hard on the brakes.
It's hard on the engine.

40:43.775 --> 40:47.546
It's point and squirt
and bark and yelp.

40:47.546 --> 40:49.681
It is vicious.

40:52.117 --> 40:56.855
But there is nothing here
which has flummoxed the M2.

40:56.855 --> 41:00.559
This thing is
an absolute masterpiece.

41:03.394 --> 41:06.532
Like I said,
it is the best M car

41:06.532 --> 41:08.233
BMW has ever made.

41:11.236 --> 41:13.639
You may think
it's mad to suggest

41:13.639 --> 41:16.207
the cheapest M car
is the best,

41:16.207 --> 41:18.043
but look at it this way,

41:18.043 --> 41:21.379
this track is a lot cheaper
than Silverstone.

41:21.379 --> 41:24.182
And I know which one
I'd rather drive round.

41:30.388 --> 41:32.558
[CHEERING]

41:36.427 --> 41:38.463
Go drive an M2.
Unbelievable.

41:38.463 --> 41:41.567
What?

41:41.567 --> 41:45.103
Why is there that zigzag
at Old Lady's House?

41:45.103 --> 41:47.272
- That wasn't there when I went.
- No, that wasn't.

41:47.272 --> 41:49.340
But after you'd left,
we discovered there is

41:49.340 --> 41:52.110
an unexploded Second
World War bomb, seriously,

41:52.110 --> 41:55.914
right where the track was,
so we had to go round it.

41:55.914 --> 41:57.448
- Fair enough.
- Let me get this right.

41:57.448 --> 42:01.219
At our track,
there's trees, animals,

42:01.219 --> 42:03.054
moisture, electricity,

42:03.054 --> 42:05.090
a house,
and an unexploded bomb?

42:05.090 --> 42:08.026
Yeah. Like I said, it's
the most dangerous track
in the world.

42:08.026 --> 42:12.030
Honestly, it makes Imola
look like a duvet. Honestly.

42:12.030 --> 42:15.801
Anyway, all the cars that
we test at the Eboladrome

42:15.801 --> 42:17.636
will do a timed lap.

42:17.636 --> 42:20.205
And to make sure it's
a completely level
playing field,

42:20.205 --> 42:24.175
they will all be driven
by the same racing driver.

42:24.175 --> 42:26.011
AUDIENCE: Ooh!

42:26.011 --> 42:28.246
We thought about this.
We gave it some thought.

42:28.246 --> 42:30.148
How clever is that? Now...

42:30.148 --> 42:31.617
[LAUGHTER]

42:31.617 --> 42:33.985
The thing is,
Amazon insisted

42:33.985 --> 42:35.621
that the racing driver
in question

42:35.621 --> 42:37.656
should be from this side
of the pond.

42:37.656 --> 42:41.727
So we went to something
called NASCAR?

42:41.727 --> 42:44.362
And we found one.
We shipped him to England

42:44.362 --> 42:47.633
and then we introduced him
to the complicated procedure

42:47.633 --> 42:51.502
which involves turning right.

42:51.502 --> 42:52.904
He's called Mike Skinner,

42:52.904 --> 42:55.506
but we know him simply as
"the American."

42:55.506 --> 42:57.208
We should warn you

42:57.208 --> 43:00.178
that some of his views
are quite strong.

43:00.178 --> 43:02.881
Yes, he has very specific
views, for example,

43:02.881 --> 43:05.283
on cars that have engines
with fewer than eight cylinders.

43:05.283 --> 43:07.485
- Communist.
- Or more than eight cylinders.

43:07.485 --> 43:10.722
- Communist.
- Or cars that have
their engine in the middle.

43:10.722 --> 43:12.724
Communist.

43:12.724 --> 43:15.827
Everything that isn't American
really with a V8 is communist.

43:15.827 --> 43:18.897
So let's see how he gets on
with the M2.

43:18.897 --> 43:20.932
There he is.

43:20.932 --> 43:23.268
Looking utterly bewildered.

43:25.003 --> 43:28.306
But he's off.
A skitter of a wheel spin.

43:28.306 --> 43:30.742
And immediately
he's onto the Isn't Straight.

43:30.742 --> 43:33.211
There is a right there
that will have confused him.

43:33.211 --> 43:34.746
Now a left,
he'll be good at that.

43:34.746 --> 43:35.781
Now he can open the taps.

43:35.781 --> 43:40.251
Three liters, six cylinders.

43:40.251 --> 43:41.953
This thing wouldn't pull
a greasy string

43:41.953 --> 43:43.855
out of a dog's ass.

43:43.855 --> 43:48.727
JEREMY: I've literally no
idea what he's talking about.

43:48.727 --> 43:51.462
Where I come from,
this ain't a car.

43:51.462 --> 43:53.699
It's a cry for help.

43:53.699 --> 43:55.533
JEREMY: Whatever.

43:55.533 --> 43:57.903
He's through the final corner
on the Isn't Straight.

43:57.903 --> 44:00.706
Into Your Name Here.
Hard on the brakes.

44:00.706 --> 44:02.708
Grabbing the stick,

44:02.708 --> 44:04.710
which is on the left-hand
side of where he's sitting,

44:04.710 --> 44:06.177
and turning in.

44:06.177 --> 44:08.379
See what I mean?
No understeer at all.

44:08.379 --> 44:10.481
Damn tracks are narrower
than my driveway.

44:10.481 --> 44:13.284
Yeah, that's 'cause it doesn't
have a monster truck on it.

44:13.284 --> 44:17.155
Wonder which one of them
came up with this thing.

44:17.155 --> 44:20.358
The tall one? The short one?
Or the one with the girly hair?

44:20.358 --> 44:23.561
JEREMY: Okay, coming up
to Old Lady's House.

44:23.561 --> 44:25.030
Hard on the brakes.

44:25.030 --> 44:27.933
Turning in, round
the unexploded bomb,

44:27.933 --> 44:30.568
and now opening
the taps again.

44:30.568 --> 44:33.104
No turbo lag at all,

44:33.104 --> 44:35.506
as he hammers down
the bumpy back straight

44:35.506 --> 44:37.342
towards Sub Station.

44:37.342 --> 44:39.177
This is a 90-left,

44:39.177 --> 44:41.046
new Tarmac
but it held it well.

44:41.046 --> 44:44.082
One more 90-left to go
through Field Of Sheep.

44:44.082 --> 44:47.185
And he's done it well.
And across the line.

44:47.185 --> 44:49.120
[CHEERING]

44:50.956 --> 44:53.624
First one. That's good.

44:53.624 --> 44:55.193
He's great.

44:55.193 --> 44:58.163
He's great going
left and right. Amazing.

44:58.163 --> 45:00.031
To make sure that the M2--

45:00.031 --> 45:02.968
that wasn't on the lap board
all by itself,

45:02.968 --> 45:06.004
we got the American to put
other benchmark cars--

45:06.004 --> 45:10.141
we call them benchmark cars,
he calls them communist--

45:10.141 --> 45:12.177
around the track,
to see what's what.

45:12.177 --> 45:14.112
There they all are:
McLaren, Audi and so forth.

45:14.112 --> 45:16.314
Hang on a minute.
We saw a Ferrari 488

45:16.314 --> 45:17.783
at the track
in the film earlier on.

45:17.783 --> 45:19.017
Why isn't that on there?

45:19.017 --> 45:21.186
Because Ferrari
wouldn't let us time it.

45:21.186 --> 45:23.088
- Wouldn't let us?
- No.

45:23.088 --> 45:25.791
So the Ferrari LaFerrari
can't go on the road

45:25.791 --> 45:28.259
- or run on electric only?
- No.

45:28.259 --> 45:30.128
And the 488
can't do a timed lap?

45:30.128 --> 45:32.663
Ferrari are quite tricky to
deal with from time to time.

45:32.663 --> 45:35.901
Let's just put it that way
and move on. It's time to see

45:35.901 --> 45:38.236
where the M2 goes
on that board.

45:38.236 --> 45:41.072
Let's have a look.
Let's put it on.

45:41.072 --> 45:43.308
- Oh!
- RICHARD: Ha-ha!

45:43.308 --> 45:44.976
Wow! Wow!

45:44.976 --> 45:48.814
"I think it's the best M car
they've ever made."

45:50.448 --> 45:52.517
Not my words.

45:52.517 --> 45:54.853
"I prefer it to all the others
that are quicker than it."

45:54.853 --> 45:57.823
- Yes, it's--
- The one you should have,

45:57.823 --> 46:00.091
if you want one that's slower
than all the other M cars.

46:00.091 --> 46:02.427
It's better.
It's only two seconds--

46:02.427 --> 46:05.396
- It's quicker than a Civic.
- Yeah.

46:05.396 --> 46:07.032
But it's slower than--

46:07.032 --> 46:08.834
If you had a choice
of M cars, lined them up,

46:08.834 --> 46:11.302
and said,
"I'd like the fastest,"
it wouldn't be that one.

46:11.302 --> 46:14.739
- Shut up.
- Better in every single way?

46:14.739 --> 46:17.208
- You said that.
- I don't care.
Have you driven one?

46:17.208 --> 46:20.178
- I have.
- It's fabulous.

46:20.178 --> 46:22.848
It's a brilliant car.
It really honestly is.

46:22.848 --> 46:25.951
It's a shame we can't take
the track round the world
with us.

46:25.951 --> 46:29.087
Because if we did, we could
invite celebrities to drive
round it

46:29.087 --> 46:31.122
and we could keep
a score sheet

46:31.122 --> 46:33.358
of who was the fastest.

46:33.358 --> 46:35.393
[LAUGHTER]

46:35.393 --> 46:36.862
No, I don't like it!

46:36.862 --> 46:38.596
I don't like it, no.

46:38.596 --> 46:41.166
- I don't think it would work.
- Nobody wants to watch that.

46:41.166 --> 46:44.102
I'm not sure that they do.
Anyway, we've got a better idea,

46:44.102 --> 46:46.137
Okay, for our celebrities.

46:46.137 --> 46:49.207
We're calling it
Celebrity Brain Crash,

46:49.207 --> 46:51.542
and we had a sting made
for that as well.

46:58.984 --> 47:02.020
That is terrible.

47:02.020 --> 47:04.255
I don't like to use this...

47:04.255 --> 47:05.891
[CHEERING]

47:07.558 --> 47:09.928
RICHARD: It's just terrible.

47:09.928 --> 47:13.899
Who is gonna say,
"I'm gonna watch that
new Amazon car show.

47:13.899 --> 47:16.634
Henry VIII's head explodes"?

47:16.634 --> 47:20.105
Why is there smoke coming out
of Brad Pitt's head?

47:20.105 --> 47:22.640
What are we trying to say?

47:22.640 --> 47:24.609
- No, we're not.
- No, we're not saying that.

47:25.911 --> 47:27.812
Not that.

47:27.812 --> 47:29.647
That is a terrible sting,

47:29.647 --> 47:32.717
but the machine itself
isn't terrible at all.

47:32.717 --> 47:35.686
It's used to measure
somebody's mental agility,

47:35.686 --> 47:37.522
their observational skills

47:37.522 --> 47:40.191
and their ability
to multi-task.

47:40.191 --> 47:42.227
It's actually based
on a machine

47:42.227 --> 47:44.262
that's used
to test fighter pilots

47:44.262 --> 47:46.297
who want to join
the Royal Air Force

47:46.297 --> 47:49.200
which, as we all know, is the
finest and greatest air force

47:49.200 --> 47:52.503
- in the world.
- [JEERING]

47:52.503 --> 47:56.141
What do you mean, "Boo"?
What do you mean, "Boo"?
What?

47:56.141 --> 47:59.110
If that was true, we wouldn't
have to help you every time
you get in trouble.

47:59.110 --> 48:02.948
[UPROAR, CHEERING]

48:07.785 --> 48:09.620
I'll hold myself back here.

48:09.620 --> 48:13.391
Now, hold on. You lot can
grumble as much as you like,

48:13.391 --> 48:16.394
but we edit this show
and we're British,

48:16.394 --> 48:18.396
so you'll just get cut out.

48:18.396 --> 48:21.566
- [BOOING]
- We're all in agreement.

48:21.566 --> 48:25.770
That the Royal Air Force is
better than the US Air Force.

48:25.770 --> 48:29.407
[CHANTING]
USA! USA! USA!

48:29.407 --> 48:31.809
- [JEERING]
- We're all in agreement

48:31.809 --> 48:35.480
the Royal Air Force is better
than all the other air forces
in the world.

48:35.480 --> 48:37.448
[JEERING]

48:38.416 --> 48:40.751
We're all now in agreement.

48:40.751 --> 48:42.520
The Royal Air Force is--

48:42.520 --> 48:44.522
is the best air force
in the world.

48:44.522 --> 48:46.591
[BOOING]

48:46.591 --> 48:50.061
So we're all in agreement
the Royal Air Force
is quite good.

48:50.061 --> 48:52.998
- [JEERING]
- That will do. That will do.

48:52.998 --> 48:56.701
So let's get back
to Celebrity Brain Crash

48:56.701 --> 48:58.636
and meet our first-ever guest.

48:58.636 --> 49:00.471
Normally on other shows,

49:00.471 --> 49:02.507
the guest will come through
a sparkly curtain,

49:02.507 --> 49:05.810
wave a bit and then sit down,
but not here.

49:05.810 --> 49:09.614
Oh, yes, our guests
make a proper arrival.

49:09.614 --> 49:12.750
And on that note,
let's meet tonight's star.

49:12.750 --> 49:15.420
He has been in pretty much

49:15.420 --> 49:18.256
every single movie franchise
there is

49:18.256 --> 49:20.291
apart from Bridget Jones.

49:20.291 --> 49:22.293
No, he was Bridget Jones.

49:22.293 --> 49:24.562
- Was he?
- No.

49:24.562 --> 49:27.498
But it doesn't matter.
He was in the Bourne  films.

49:27.498 --> 49:29.200
He was in the
Mission Impossible films,

49:29.200 --> 49:30.568
the Avengers films,

49:30.568 --> 49:34.139
and right now
he is 10,000 feet above us,

49:34.139 --> 49:36.707
waiting to make
one hell of an entrance.

49:36.707 --> 49:39.177
Ladies and gentlemen,
Jeremy Renner!

49:39.177 --> 49:41.446
[CHEERING]

49:41.446 --> 49:45.050
There he is. There he is,
that's his plane.

49:45.050 --> 49:47.118
[CHEERING]

49:50.388 --> 49:52.390
Hold on, everybody.
Here he comes.

49:52.390 --> 49:55.126
He is ready to jump.

49:55.126 --> 49:56.827
I'm ready!

49:56.827 --> 50:00.065
He is ready to jump.
And there he goes!

50:00.065 --> 50:01.599
RICHARD:
That is amazing

50:01.599 --> 50:03.401
to see him doing
his own stunts.

50:03.401 --> 50:06.937
JEREMY: Yeah, I know.
And he is looking good!

50:06.937 --> 50:09.006
When he gets here,

50:09.006 --> 50:11.709
I do want to talk to him
about that Bourne Legacy
film.

50:11.709 --> 50:14.445
A: what it was like to punch
Shane Jacobson.

50:14.445 --> 50:17.515
And, B...
Ooh, hang on.

50:17.515 --> 50:20.751
He's leaving this terribly late.

50:20.751 --> 50:22.687
[NERVOUS LAUGHTER]

50:25.390 --> 50:27.625
[AUDIENCE CLAMORING]

50:27.625 --> 50:29.560
[APPLAUSE]

50:39.404 --> 50:42.573
Right.

50:42.573 --> 50:44.875
Does that mean
he's not coming on, then?

50:44.875 --> 50:47.812
No, James, he's not.

50:47.812 --> 50:51.116
It's okay, though.
We anticipated
this sort of thing,

50:51.116 --> 50:53.151
so we got
a back-up guest ready.

50:53.151 --> 50:55.186
Uh...

50:55.186 --> 50:57.555
He was in Man From Uncle.

50:57.555 --> 51:00.991
He was in Lone Ranger.
He was both twins

51:00.991 --> 51:02.760
in The Social Network.

51:02.760 --> 51:05.530
And his new film is called
Nocturnal Animals.

51:05.530 --> 51:07.565
We haven't had time,
unfortunately,

51:07.565 --> 51:09.500
to organize
a dramatic entrance,

51:09.500 --> 51:12.337
but I hope you'll give him
a warm welcome nevertheless.

51:12.337 --> 51:14.739
Ladies and gentlemen,
Armie Hammer!

51:15.973 --> 51:17.842
There he is.

51:18.943 --> 51:20.978
Oh, my...

51:20.978 --> 51:22.680
Jesus!

51:22.680 --> 51:24.482
Is that a snake?

51:24.482 --> 51:26.384
- It's a snake.
- That's a rattlesnake.

51:26.384 --> 51:28.386
- Is it?
- Yeah.

51:28.386 --> 51:31.289
He's being killed.
Quiet, everyone.

51:31.289 --> 51:33.324
Quiet, please.

51:33.324 --> 51:35.360
There's literally
nothing we can do.

51:35.360 --> 51:37.395
He's yards away from us.

51:37.395 --> 51:39.063
Snakes are like herds
of them.

51:39.063 --> 51:41.766
- They hunt in packs.
- Yeah, they're pack animals.

51:41.766 --> 51:44.535
Does that mean
he's not coming on either?

51:44.535 --> 51:47.805
No, James, he's finished
writhing around in agony.

51:47.805 --> 51:49.840
And now he's dead.

51:49.840 --> 51:51.876
So that is a no.

51:51.876 --> 51:53.711
Well, uh...

51:53.711 --> 51:56.281
maybe there's somebody famous
in the audience.

51:56.281 --> 51:58.283
That's unlikely.

51:58.283 --> 52:00.751
No. Seriously,
you know Carol Vorderman?

52:00.751 --> 52:03.321
She rang me this morning
from an air show nearby

52:03.321 --> 52:06.357
and said,
can she come to the show?

52:06.357 --> 52:08.359
I know you don't know
who Carol Vorderman is.

52:08.359 --> 52:10.895
She's a huge, huge,
huge star in the UK.

52:10.895 --> 52:12.930
She started out on
a program called Countdown

52:12.930 --> 52:15.200
and established herself as
being unbelievably brilliant,

52:15.200 --> 52:17.202
a fantastic mathematician

52:17.202 --> 52:19.237
and very beautiful.

52:19.237 --> 52:22.540
Yes, she's also dead.

52:22.540 --> 52:24.074
What?

52:24.074 --> 52:27.878
- What?
- She's dead.

52:27.878 --> 52:30.648
- How did that happen?
- I don't know.
I'm not a pathologist!

52:30.648 --> 52:33.284
But she's dead
is what she is.

52:33.284 --> 52:35.286
- Seriously?
- Yes!

52:35.286 --> 52:38.289
- Christ.
- Problem.

52:38.289 --> 52:40.591
What are we gonna do?

52:40.591 --> 52:41.859
Um...

52:41.859 --> 52:44.229
Jesus, look at that out there.
It's like a--

52:44.229 --> 52:45.863
It's just littered
with corpses.

52:45.863 --> 52:48.333
[LAUGHTER]

52:48.333 --> 52:51.836
Lads, I don't think
this bit is working.

52:51.836 --> 52:53.238
Let's drop

52:53.238 --> 52:55.573
Celebrity Brain Crash
this week.

52:55.573 --> 52:57.708
We'll do it again in
South Africa next week,

52:57.708 --> 52:59.744
and I think people will
have forgotten all this.

52:59.744 --> 53:02.513
- They might not.
- I think they will.

53:02.513 --> 53:04.949
We'll just skip over it now.
It's not gonna happen.

53:04.949 --> 53:07.285
That's okay, 'cause we
can back to the cars.

53:07.285 --> 53:10.388
- Yes! Moving on!
- [CHEERING]

53:11.689 --> 53:14.091
- Don't look.
- Yes, don't look.

53:14.091 --> 53:15.460
This week--

53:15.460 --> 53:17.762
This week we are trying
to find out

53:17.762 --> 53:20.531
which of the new breed of
hybrid hypercars is the best.

53:20.531 --> 53:22.900
Yes. On day one
at the track in Portugal,

53:22.900 --> 53:26.404
we established that
the McLaren P1 is a mentalist,

53:26.404 --> 53:30.174
that the Porsche 918
is a very good milk float,

53:30.174 --> 53:33.444
and that the Ferrari LaFerrari
can do nothing at all.

53:34.345 --> 53:36.381
Some of that is true.

53:36.381 --> 53:39.484
But now, day two.

53:49.660 --> 53:51.629
JEREMY:
We began by lining up

53:51.629 --> 53:54.365
the three most exciting cars
on the planet

53:54.365 --> 53:58.002
for the drag race
of all drag races.

54:12.016 --> 54:15.686
Naturally, this meant
engaging launch control,

54:15.686 --> 54:20.024
which in the McLaren
takes about a fortnight.

54:20.024 --> 54:24.094
I have to have the drive tray
in track mode,

54:24.094 --> 54:26.331
the aero package
in sport mode,

54:26.331 --> 54:27.665
so that the rear end squats

54:27.665 --> 54:29.634
when I set off
and gives me more traction.

54:29.634 --> 54:32.870
I have to have the DRS
button pressed with my thumb

54:32.870 --> 54:36.874
to keep the rear wing open
which reduces drag obviously.

54:36.874 --> 54:39.977
Launch control in the Porsche,
left foot on the brake hard.

54:39.977 --> 54:42.012
Right foot
on the throttle hard.

54:42.012 --> 54:44.349
Light goes green, left foot
off brake. Pa-ching!

54:44.349 --> 54:46.751
Launch button,
press for two seconds.

54:46.751 --> 54:49.520
Left foot on brake.
Right foot on throttle.

54:49.520 --> 54:51.956
Press launch control,
mash the throttle,

54:51.956 --> 54:54.759
within four seconds
release the brake.

54:54.759 --> 54:57.995
Three seconds later,
I have full boost,

54:57.995 --> 55:00.431
and I have to set off
within three seconds

55:00.431 --> 55:02.833
or the entire system
disengages.

55:02.833 --> 55:05.603
I'm going to get this wrong.

55:05.603 --> 55:07.638
Just so you know.

55:07.638 --> 55:09.940
I've got a lot to do in here.

55:13.411 --> 55:15.713
[REVVING]

55:32.930 --> 55:34.832
[BEEP]

55:36.401 --> 55:39.169
I wasn't ready.

55:39.169 --> 55:41.939
Oh, my God!
That is quick!

55:45.810 --> 55:49.947
Holy mother!
Did you see that?

55:49.947 --> 55:53.183
[BLEEP] me!
Jesus [BLEEP] Christ!

55:53.183 --> 55:55.119
It's all over the place.

56:00.458 --> 56:03.060
Since it was clear I'd got
all my buttons wrong,

56:03.060 --> 56:06.497
the chaps agreed
to another run.

56:06.497 --> 56:08.533
Sit rep,
the lights went green

56:08.533 --> 56:10.601
before the boost was ready,

56:10.601 --> 56:12.770
and I had the DRS button
still pressed

56:12.770 --> 56:15.440
when I got to the end,
which meant I had no downforce,

56:15.440 --> 56:18.643
which meant--
Well, poo came out.

56:18.643 --> 56:22.713
This time I'm gonna do it
with more drag,

56:22.713 --> 56:25.315
which will slow me down,
but I will be able to stop

56:25.315 --> 56:27.452
without killing myself.

56:29.454 --> 56:32.457
[REVVING]

56:32.457 --> 56:34.559
KERS system charged. Right.

56:39.196 --> 56:41.566
JEREMY: Boost building.

56:44.368 --> 56:46.504
Three, two...

56:50.475 --> 56:52.543
And we are away!
What a start!

56:55.312 --> 56:57.715
The Porsche has got off
to a flyer.

56:59.216 --> 57:01.151
Oh, balls!

57:02.620 --> 57:04.889
180, 190, 210.

57:06.691 --> 57:08.726
230 kilometers an hour.

57:14.198 --> 57:16.967
That wasn't very good.

57:16.967 --> 57:20.204
Because James had
somehow messed up that time,

57:20.204 --> 57:22.673
and because this test
was about the cars,

57:22.673 --> 57:25.209
we decided to go again.

57:30.347 --> 57:31.782
It's a rocket ship.

57:33.518 --> 57:35.620
For England!

57:37.254 --> 57:38.989
No, no!

57:44.729 --> 57:46.997
Okay, we have all three
won this now.

57:49.634 --> 57:51.902
JEREMY: Determined
to find a definitive

57:51.902 --> 57:55.405
one-two-three
finishing order,

57:55.405 --> 57:57.274
we ran again.

57:57.274 --> 57:59.209
[BEEP]

58:02.212 --> 58:06.216
Another totally different
result there, gentlemen.

58:07.384 --> 58:08.819
And again.

58:11.956 --> 58:15.760
That's a different result
again.

58:15.760 --> 58:17.895
JEREMY: And again?

58:23.100 --> 58:25.369
At this point,
we decided to call

58:25.369 --> 58:26.937
a halt to proceedings,

58:26.937 --> 58:31.609
because we had reached
a scientific conclusion.

58:31.609 --> 58:35.045
It turns out it doesn't really
matter which car you buy,

58:35.045 --> 58:37.281
it all depends on your shoes.

58:37.281 --> 58:38.983
Now, this is a TOD loafer.

58:38.983 --> 58:42.052
Slightly worn
to get a crisper jump

58:42.052 --> 58:44.254
off the brake pedal,
and it's immediate.

58:44.254 --> 58:47.191
- This is a Converse.
- There's more sponge
in there than I thought.

58:47.191 --> 58:50.160
See, Adidas, they weren't
thinking that through.

58:50.160 --> 58:53.330
- So, as you lift
your foot up--
- It's a millisecond.

58:53.330 --> 58:54.699
I know you've got KERS,

58:54.699 --> 58:56.266
I know you've got
a 6.3-litre V12,

58:56.266 --> 58:58.836
and I know that launch
control system is amazing,

58:58.836 --> 59:00.237
but it's all let down

59:00.237 --> 59:02.206
by the sponginess
of the Adidas shoe.

59:02.206 --> 59:04.441
So they should sell you
the car and the shoes.

59:04.441 --> 59:06.977
No, have you got the correct
shoes and have you worn them in?

59:06.977 --> 59:09.013
- Exactly.
- Fresh shoes, lads.

59:09.013 --> 59:13.217
- I just need to--
- You need to skid about.
There we go.

59:13.217 --> 59:15.820
With that sorted,

59:15.820 --> 59:18.055
it was time to bring in
a racing driver

59:18.055 --> 59:21.926
to see which of our cars
could do the fastest lap.

59:21.926 --> 59:25.262
Our resident American
said he wasn't interested,

59:25.262 --> 59:28.265
because all three cars
are probably communist.

59:28.265 --> 59:31.636
So instead, we went
for a Belgian chap--

59:31.636 --> 59:33.170
[GUNFIRE]

59:33.170 --> 59:36.807
...who's done Formula One
and Formula E,

59:36.807 --> 59:39.343
Jerome d'Ambrosio.

59:44.314 --> 59:46.016
Jerome took the cars out

59:46.016 --> 59:48.686
to get a sense of how
they handled.

1:00:05.002 --> 1:00:06.837
And when he'd finished,

1:00:06.837 --> 1:00:08.639
we were interested to hear

1:00:08.639 --> 1:00:10.607
his professional opinion.

1:00:10.607 --> 1:00:12.943
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

1:00:54.785 --> 1:00:57.421
RICHARD: At this point,
word reached us that Jeremy

1:00:57.421 --> 1:01:01.091
was taking liberties
with the subtitling machine.

1:01:02.459 --> 1:01:05.429
So we moved on
to the big event:

1:01:05.429 --> 1:01:08.098
the timed laps.

1:01:13.437 --> 1:01:15.472
Once the mechanics had
finished their preparations,

1:01:15.472 --> 1:01:18.408
the three speed traps
were activated.

1:01:21.879 --> 1:01:24.548
And the Ferrari LaFerrari
took its place

1:01:24.548 --> 1:01:27.051
on the start line.

1:01:28.185 --> 1:01:30.220
Look how good it looks there.

1:01:30.220 --> 1:01:33.557
This is just wasting time.
It's wasting rubber and fuel.

1:01:33.557 --> 1:01:35.392
No, this is like
an amuse-bouche.

1:01:35.392 --> 1:01:39.096
Yeah, it is. You have ordered
the duck and sherry trifle.

1:01:39.096 --> 1:01:42.833
- And you're a melon ball.
- I'm not even listening.

1:01:45.770 --> 1:01:47.938
[BEEPING]

1:01:58.448 --> 1:02:03.453
Gentlemen, it is doing
231.4 kilometers an hour

1:02:03.453 --> 1:02:05.589
at the end of the straight.

1:02:05.589 --> 1:02:09.193
It's about the same speed
as a Golf diesel,
something like that.

1:02:22.840 --> 1:02:26.276
194.9.

1:02:26.276 --> 1:02:28.112
Going down the hill
using gravity.

1:02:28.112 --> 1:02:30.314
- Is he stopping off
for shopping?
- He must be.

1:02:45.963 --> 1:02:48.098
Here he is.

1:02:54.604 --> 1:02:59.343
- James, if you want
to get a cup of tea.
- We've warmed the track.

1:02:59.343 --> 1:03:03.848
RICHARD: Next it was the turn
of the Porsche 918.

1:03:03.848 --> 1:03:06.350
How much faster will it go
because of the stripes?

1:03:06.350 --> 1:03:07.351
Much.

1:03:22.299 --> 1:03:24.134
231 point...

1:03:24.134 --> 1:03:26.170
So he's faster
than the Ferrari.

1:03:35.679 --> 1:03:38.182
RICHARD: 183.0.

1:03:38.182 --> 1:03:41.785
Way, way,
way slower than him.

1:03:41.785 --> 1:03:43.921
Don't forget between here
and the next measuring point,

1:03:43.921 --> 1:03:46.590
Okay, you've got
four slow corners,

1:03:46.590 --> 1:03:49.259
and those are the ones
where the Porsche
is gonna make up time.

1:03:51.161 --> 1:03:52.362
Because of the
four-wheel steering.

1:03:52.362 --> 1:03:56.033
- Like a Honda Prelude?
- No!

1:04:09.646 --> 1:04:12.449
- 110 point what?
- One.

1:04:12.449 --> 1:04:16.386
So, almost to a tenth
of a kilometer an hour,
the same speed as you.

1:04:21.258 --> 1:04:24.061
RICHARD: Here he comes.
He's firing noises.

1:04:25.362 --> 1:04:26.931
There it is.
Look at that.

1:04:29.833 --> 1:04:33.337
JEREMY: Finally, it was
the turn of the psycho killer.

1:04:33.337 --> 1:04:36.040
The trickiest,
the edgiest of the three.

1:04:37.541 --> 1:04:39.443
But I was so confident
it'd win,

1:04:39.443 --> 1:04:43.047
I was prepared
to take a massive gamble.

1:04:44.381 --> 1:04:49.086
If the McLaren
isn't the fastest,

1:04:49.086 --> 1:04:51.956
you two can knock
my house down.

1:04:51.956 --> 1:04:54.124
- What?
- Knock it down.

1:04:54.124 --> 1:04:56.994
- What, your house?
- Yeah, and I mean that.

1:04:56.994 --> 1:05:00.664
That's how confident I am
that that will be the fastest.

1:05:00.664 --> 1:05:04.801
- You know we will do that?
- Yeah.

1:05:04.801 --> 1:05:07.271
- It's a serious bet?
- Yeah.

1:05:07.271 --> 1:05:09.839
- Fine.
- If that's not the fastest,

1:05:09.839 --> 1:05:12.409
- we can knock your house down?
- Yup.

1:05:12.409 --> 1:05:14.644
You know where it is.
You've both been.

1:05:14.644 --> 1:05:16.613
I'd love to knock it down.

1:05:23.020 --> 1:05:25.222
Here we go.
A lot riding on this.

1:05:37.834 --> 1:05:41.305
235.9.

1:05:41.305 --> 1:05:44.008
Okay, it's fastest at the end
of the first straight.

1:05:48.712 --> 1:05:50.747
Would you like to come
to my house for dinner?

1:05:50.747 --> 1:05:52.549
Yes. Can I bring a bulldozer?

1:06:00.324 --> 1:06:02.192
188.3.

1:06:02.192 --> 1:06:04.228
That is worryingly quick.
Brisk.

1:06:04.228 --> 1:06:06.063
It's quite brisk?

1:06:06.063 --> 1:06:08.865
We don't know how fast it's
going around the tight turns.

1:06:08.865 --> 1:06:11.435
Might have been doing
two kilometers an hour
around here.

1:06:23.180 --> 1:06:25.382
Where is he?

1:06:25.382 --> 1:06:26.616
Crashed.

1:06:44.068 --> 1:06:46.936
With that,
back to the tent.

1:06:46.936 --> 1:06:49.539
[CHEERING]

1:06:54.811 --> 1:06:56.646
Thank you so much. Now...

1:06:56.646 --> 1:06:58.682
I want to make it
absolutely plain,

1:06:58.682 --> 1:07:00.717
'cause I know this matters
to anoraks,

1:07:00.717 --> 1:07:06.156
all three cars were running
on exactly the same sort
of tires.

1:07:06.156 --> 1:07:08.758
Yes, same tires, same track,
same driver.

1:07:08.758 --> 1:07:11.095
So the times
are down to the cars.

1:07:11.095 --> 1:07:14.331
Yup. And now it is time
to reveal those times.

1:07:14.331 --> 1:07:16.533
Let me just make it
absolutely clear.

1:07:16.533 --> 1:07:18.102
We don't know what they are.

1:07:18.102 --> 1:07:20.270
The producers have kept them
from us.

1:07:20.270 --> 1:07:21.605
- They're top secret.
- Yup.

1:07:21.605 --> 1:07:23.773
So, let's put
the scoreboard up,

1:07:23.773 --> 1:07:25.008
and let's begin with

1:07:25.008 --> 1:07:27.644
the Ferrari LaFerrari,
I believe.

1:07:27.644 --> 1:07:30.114
Let's see what it did it in,
please.

1:07:33.883 --> 1:07:36.953
We don't know
if that's any good, do we?

1:07:36.953 --> 1:07:39.323
Let's move on
and do the Porsche next.

1:07:39.323 --> 1:07:40.790
What did the Porsche
do it in?

1:07:42.192 --> 1:07:46.630
Oh, yes! 1:54.2!

1:07:46.630 --> 1:07:49.533
Yes! Yes! You see?

1:07:49.533 --> 1:07:51.668
You said it would mince
the Porsche.

1:07:51.668 --> 1:07:55.038
And it didn't mince it.
It was slower than the Porsche.

1:07:55.038 --> 1:07:56.906
I told you
it's just a melon ball.

1:07:56.906 --> 1:07:58.842
It's slower than my car,

1:07:58.842 --> 1:08:01.378
which was faster
than your car.

1:08:01.378 --> 1:08:03.613
0.2 of a second,
and it looks better.

1:08:03.613 --> 1:08:06.350
Yeah, it did in my mirror
where it belongs getting
smaller.

1:08:06.350 --> 1:08:07.951
It's a melon ball,
and it lost.

1:08:07.951 --> 1:08:09.186
- Hammond.
- What?

1:08:09.186 --> 1:08:10.954
- Calm down.
- All right.

1:08:10.954 --> 1:08:12.156
Because now we must bring up

1:08:12.156 --> 1:08:13.723
the time that really matters.

1:08:13.723 --> 1:08:17.294
The one where
a lot's at stake.

1:08:17.294 --> 1:08:18.295
The McLaren...
[CLEARS THROAT]

1:08:18.295 --> 1:08:19.463
The McLaren P1.

1:08:19.463 --> 1:08:22.166
- Are you nervous? Sure?
- No. No.

1:08:22.166 --> 1:08:23.500
- A little bit?
- No!

1:08:23.500 --> 1:08:25.269
- I'm not nervous.
- Why be nervous?

1:08:25.269 --> 1:08:26.470
You could get, like,
a shopping trolley

1:08:26.470 --> 1:08:28.705
and keep all your things
in it.

1:08:28.705 --> 1:08:31.575
Make some new friends
under a bridge somewhere.

1:08:31.575 --> 1:08:33.843
- Hammond.
- I'd say sell your body
but don't do that.

1:08:33.843 --> 1:08:36.580
Be quiet! Let's--

1:08:36.580 --> 1:08:39.316
Let's bring up the time
of the P1. Here we go.

1:08:39.316 --> 1:08:42.419
- Oh, God.
- Where is it?

1:08:46.823 --> 1:08:50.093
[UPROAR]

1:08:50.093 --> 1:08:52.462
Yes!

1:08:56.666 --> 1:09:00.404
That is funny.
Because you said...

1:09:00.404 --> 1:09:03.207
the fastest,
but it's not the fastest.

1:09:03.207 --> 1:09:05.209
It's the slowest!

1:09:05.209 --> 1:09:08.445
Ladies and gentlemen,
journalist, broadcaster

1:09:08.445 --> 1:09:11.881
and homeless man,
Jeremy Clarkson.

1:09:11.881 --> 1:09:13.817
[CHEERING]

1:09:18.788 --> 1:09:23.560
That's what it is.
That's what it is.

1:09:23.560 --> 1:09:26.363
You're not really going
to knock my house down?

1:09:26.363 --> 1:09:28.865
Yes, we are.

1:09:28.865 --> 1:09:30.900
- A bet is a bet.
- That's the deal.

1:09:30.900 --> 1:09:33.637
- And we're going to film it.
- No, but the thing is,

1:09:33.637 --> 1:09:36.240
on the tires that the
McLaren can be bought with,

1:09:36.240 --> 1:09:38.575
it was faster.

1:09:38.575 --> 1:09:40.277
We agreed right at the start

1:09:40.277 --> 1:09:43.380
we'd all run on
the same tires.

1:09:43.380 --> 1:09:45.849
That was the deal
before your car lost.

1:09:45.849 --> 1:09:47.384
So let's just...

1:09:47.384 --> 1:09:50.887
Let's just sum this
first show up, shall we?

1:09:50.887 --> 1:09:52.722
I've lost my house.

1:09:52.722 --> 1:09:55.091
- We've had a fight
with the audience.
- Big one.

1:09:55.091 --> 1:09:57.961
Somebody shot our drone down.

1:09:57.961 --> 1:10:00.664
And we've killed three
quite major celebrities.

1:10:00.664 --> 1:10:02.699
Yeah, but on the plus side,

1:10:02.699 --> 1:10:04.901
my Porsche was the fastest!

1:10:04.901 --> 1:10:06.370
[CHEERING]

1:10:10.407 --> 1:10:12.576
And on that terrible
disappointment,

1:10:12.576 --> 1:10:14.678
I'm afraid it's time to end.

1:10:14.678 --> 1:10:16.480
Thank you all very much
for coming.

1:10:16.480 --> 1:10:18.014
Thank you for watching.

1:10:18.014 --> 1:10:19.883
And we'll see you next week
in Johannesburg.

1:10:19.883 --> 1:10:21.285
Good-bye!

1:10:21.285 --> 1:10:22.952
[CHEERING]

